{"id":"1609.02730","submitter":"A. M. Rucklidge","authors":"A. M. Rucklidge and E. Knobloch","title":"Chaos in the Takens-Bogdanov bifurcation with O(2) symmetry","comments":"26 pages, 9 figures. Accepted for publication in Dynamical Systems:\n  An International Journal","journal-ref":"Dynamical Systems, 32:3, 354-373 (2017)","doi":"10.1080/14689367.2016.1239699","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Takens-Bogdanov bifurcation is a codimension two bifurcation that\nprovides a key to the presence of complex dynamics in many systems of physical\ninterest. When the system is translation-invariant in one spatial dimension\nwith no left-right preference the imposition of periodic boundary conditions\nleads to the Takens-Bogdanov bifurcation with O(2) symmetry. This bifurcation,\nanalyzed by G. Dangelmayr and E. Knobloch, Phil. Trans. R. Soc. London A 322,\n243 (1987), describes the interaction between steady states and traveling and\nstanding waves in the nonlinear regime and predicts the presence of modulated\ntraveling waves as well. The analysis reveals the presence of several global\nbifurcations near which the averaging method (used in the original analysis)\nfails. We show here, using a combination of numerical continuation and the\nconstruction of appropriate return maps, that near the global bifurcation that\nterminates the branch of modulated traveling waves, the normal form for the\nTakens-Bogdanov bifurcation admits cascades of period-doubling bifurcations as\nwell as chaotic dynamics of Shil'nikov type. Thus chaos is present arbitrarily\nclose to the codimension two point.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 9 Sep 2016 10:20:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-03"}
